<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Player's Guide for Condition Free Zone<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.57)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9097'>Steve "stairway" Griesinger</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9097&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 14, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Note:  While the deck list IS contained in this writing the contest version can be found buried deep under the top 10 list.  You would have to click on &quot;all&quot; at the bottom of the list and then click &quot;more&quot; a few times to actually find it.  ;)<br>
<br>
OVERVIEW/VENT<br>
<br>
Let me say at the outset that there is a significant difference between a deck submission and a contest deck submission -- or at least there should be.  It is very difficult, if not impossible, to fully &quot;make the case&quot; for a deck within the constraints of the contest format.  The risk is that without a full explanation a submission risks being less popular.  Perhaps that is why (as of this writing) over half of the &quot;most popular&quot; decks made no attempt whatsoever to conform to the contest guidelines.  So be it!  Or perhaps this has already been anticipated by the contest administrators.  Maybe the fine print reads similarly to the Strategist contest:  &quot;Inquest editors will be looking at the top 10 member ranked submissions WHICH MEET THE CONTEST GUIDELINES.&quot;<br>
OK, enough of that.  I got it off my chest and I feel better.<br>
<br>
Knowing this was likely to be an issue I decided to offer a more thorough explanation and argument for the card choices in the form of a player&#39;s guide.  I hope you will find it useful even if you have a difference of opinion.<br>
<br>
ASSUMPTIONS ABOUT THE METAGAME<br>
<br>
<br>
The inherent problem with any discussion about the metagame is that it does not exist in a vacuum.  The metagame is always in a state of transition.  It is fluid and transitory but never fixed.  The only thing one can do, therefore, is merely describe a moment in time -- a snap shot if you will.  That being said ANY given deck list would be making assumptions about what problems/issues their opponents are likely to pose.  All I can do is articulate those assumptions clearly so that we are all on the same page.  YOU need to be responsible for evaluating your own metagame and for making decisions and deck choices accordingly.<br>
<br>
In an attempt at full disclosure (and to make better sense of the &quot;process&quot; of adapting a deck) this is what I had been playing:<br>
<br>
Free Peoples                       Shadow<br>
Starting                           4 Orc Inquisitor<br>
Frodo, Son of Drogo                4 Morgul Skirmisher<br>
One Ring, Isildur&#39;s Bane           4 Orc Scouting Band<br>
Legolas, Greenleaf                 2 Orc Assassin<br>
Arwen                              4 Orc Ambusher<br>
                                   4 Under the Watching Eye<br>
4 Aragorn, KIE                     4 Orc Bowmen<br>
2 Aragorn&#39;s Bow                    4 Hate<br>
2 Ranger&#39;s Sword<br>
1 Sting<br>
2 PATHS<br>
1 Tale of Gil-galad<br>
1 Gwemegil<br>
1 Elven Bow<br>
1 Saga of Elendil<br>
1 Last Alliance <br>
1 Rumil<br>
1 Thrarin<br>
3 Double Shot<br>
3 Athelas<br>
2 A Ranger&#39;s Versatility<br>
2 No Strangers <br>
<br>
THE EBB AND FLOW OF MY PARTICULAR METAGAME<br>
<br>
Most shadow packages withered under a flurry of archery fire.  Most Fellowship packages crumbled as the cumulative effect of the Eye and the Bowmen took its toll.  I was master of my domain and my confidence soared.  Unfortunately, so did my arrogance.  Oh, there were subtle signs and portents along the way.  Had I not been blinded by success I might have been able to read the writing on the wall.  Cards I hadn&#39;t seen played before began to suddenly appear.  I still vividly recall the moment when I first realized what Saruman&#39;s Power meant in this instance:  goodbye to 2 No strangers, The Last Alliance, The Saga, and most unfortunate of all The Tale, since it meant the demise of Legolas.  For 2 twilight and one exertion my gleeful opponent had gotten a 6:1 card advantage!  As I tried to mentally regroup and find a way to salvage the game I was introduced to the Spies of Saruman.  Skip the archery phase?!  What fun is there in that?  Instead of whining and bandaging my wounded ego I should have opened my eyes.  The next few games would do that for me.  Gandalf was everywhere.  I&#39;ll spare you the card advantage horror stories as Sleep, Caradhras did its work on my condition heavy Sauron Orcs.  It is sufficient to say that without the Eye as a tradeoff my trackers no longer looked so appealing.  I focused all my Hate on the wizard but with only limited success.  Something had to be done -- the metagame had shifted and I was suddenly behind the curve.  One important occurrence caught my eye.  These decks all started Gandalf due to the number of support cards included.  They also all played the Pony as their site 1, ostensibly to buttress a weaker starting party.  Should I fight against this trend by creating a big high, go first and don&#39;t play the Pony deck?  Can I find a shadow set which is effective without relying on conditions?  I concluded that while a shift in fellowship decks had occurred, most players had stopped there and had NOT factored in the effect the Gandalf trend would have on their shadow decks.  It was as if they only saw half the picture.  It was as if they believed they were the only ones to reach this conclusion.  This was the opening I was looking for.<br>
<br>
THE PROCESS OF MAKING METAGAME DECISIONS - CHANGING THE FELLOWSHIP<br>
<br>
Expecting an environment to include a significant number of condition heavy shadow decks (Uruk-Spies & Sauron damage with Under the Watching Eye and Orc Bowmen) I chose to step onto the Gandalf bandwagon (or perhaps cart).<br>
<br>
Gandalf would have to be included in the starting party to justify the number of support cards.  Making the commitment to Gandalf and his tricks meant I had to find room.  Sleep could take the place of Athelas (not enough Wraith decks around to justify both).  Glamdring would replace Sting.  All the conditions would have to go (the goal remember was to find a competitive deck that was condition free).  This made room for the Servants of the Secret Fire which were a nice addition -- protecting our smaller, more vulnerable fellowship.  The Strengths of Spirit would fill the Double Shot component, actually increasing the flexibility of the deck.  Albert Dreary would find room in the ally slot essentially replacing Rumil and Thrarin.  Needing to draw into Legolas extra copies were added.  Sadly, we had to kiss Arwen goodbye.  Since Aragorn had no one left to heal he changed to the Ranger of the North.  This now gives us the opportunity to protect Frodo in an emergency or in the suicide race to win.  The PATHS stayed only because the move to Spies was trading off with the use of Snows and the Wraith decks hadn&#39;t yet evolved into the All Blades Perish version (still primarily Black Breath/Blade Tip driven).  The Versatility&#39;s stayed as well.  The combination with archery and PATHS just works so well.<br>
<br>
To save you the trouble of trying to find the &quot;Inquest&quot; version of the deck I will repeat it here:<br>
<br>
Starting<br>
Frodo, Son of Drogo<br>
One Ring, Isildurs&#39;s Bane<br>
1 Gandalf, Friend of the Shirefolk<br>
<br>
1 Glamdring<br>
4 Servant of the Secret Fire<br>
4 Strength of Spirit<br>
2 Sleep, Caradhras<br>
2 Albert Dreary<br>
4 Legolas, Greenleaf<br>
4 Aragorn, Ranger of the North<br>
2 Aragorn&#39;s Bow<br>
2 Ranger&#39;s Sword<br>
2 A Ranger&#39;s Versatility<br>
2 Power According to His Stature<br>
<br>
THE PROCESS OF MAKING METAGAME DECISIONS - CHANGING THE SHADOW<br>
<br>
Knowing/guessing/predicting that I was likely to see a massive Gandalf presence with a large commitment to condition removal (sometimes even 4 Sleeps) the question became:  Could the Sauron Orcs be competitive without using conditions?  My first inclination was to say no.  However, I didn&#39;t want to give up on these guys without ACTUALLY finding out because they had been so good to me.<br>
<br>
Under the Watching Eye had to go.  Really most effective when played early and therefore much more vulnerable to a deadly card disadvantage problem in the face of Sleep.  Without this card the trackers really do seem weak.  The Inquisitor and Skirmisher could stay since the deck could still use Hate -- a card, which if played properly, is one of the most devastating in the game (in my humble opinion).  The Band of the Eye, Morgul Hunter and Tower Lieutenant filled the tracker slots and gave us a heavier discard component.  Mainly used for reconaissance, the discard factor also occasionaly would deter a second move on a given turn by getting rid of a valuable resource.  These minions are significantly bigger than their tracker cousins (and more expensive).  Why not try making big things fierce by replacing the Eye with Enheartened Foe?  Timing this right proved most disruptive to an unsuspecting opponent.  That left the Bowmen as the only condition.  To be honest I prefer to leave the deck alone at this point and take my chances.  But the purpose here was to determine in a condition free alternative exists.  Many cards were then rotated through this slot in play testing sessions:<br>
<br>
Desperate Measures fuels the discard component and has its own unique advantages.  If burdens are not a relevant concern then spotting an orc is imminently preferable to any exertion.<br>
Orc Butchery was never as good as Desperate Measures.<br>
Forces of Mordor sometimes made a difference but not often enough.<br>
Mordor&#39;s Strength really competed with Enheartened Foe but was also tried in conjunction with it -- overexertion was the main concern with this combination.<br>
Shadow&#39;s Reach had a narrow but often potent impact.<br>
In fact, the last card put through the play test gauntlet was Orc Scimitar.  And it began to work.<br>
<br>
Does it look like it should?  Do I care what it looks like?  Am I arguing that this is the &quot;best&quot; shadow package available at this time?  Am I saying that this is &quot;better&quot; than a Wraith approach which uses Relentless Charge and All Blades Perish?  Of course I am not.  All I am saying is that in this context it worked.  It may not look like it on paper but it works just the same.  Will it work for you?  I have no idea.  But for this moment in time, with this type of opponent, it was an effective adaptation to the environment.<br>
<br>
Shadow<br>
<br>
4 Orc Inquisitor<br>
4 Morgul Skirmisher<br>
4 Morgul Hunter<br>
4 Band of the Eye<br>
2 Tower Lt<br>
4 Hate<br>
4 Enheartened Foe<br>
4 Orc Scimitar<br>
<br>
BIDDING STRATEGY/ADVENTURE DECK ANALYSIS<br>
<br>
ASSUMING most of my opponents are starting Gandalf and bidding high to ensure the Pony we are left with difficult choices.  Bid high and start without the Pony (alternate deck design) or bid low and follow.  I chose the latter strategy when designing this deck.<br>
<br>
Site 1.  The Prancing Pony.  Chosen as the first site to guarantee that against Wraith decks which choose to defer I would start with Aragorn.  On the other hand I included 4 copies of Aragorn in the deck on the chance that I played an opponent looking to thwart the Pony start.<br>
Site 2.  Breeland Forest/Weathertop.  The choice of this site became something of a dilemma once the decision to bid low and follow was made.  The umbrella goal was to overwhelm someone at site 2.  Weathertop or Weather Hills would fit the bill both adding 3 twilight to the pool.<br>
(MATH INTERLUDE)<br>
The goal was to have a potential 16 strength monster at site 2 -- enough to overwhelm either Gandalf (base 6/ +1 spotting Frodo and +1 spotting Aragorn = 8) or Aragorn (base 8).  Adding 4 to the pool to play Aragorn -- adding 3 to move the fellowship -- and 3 more for the site would total 10.  Could it be done?  Well, Band of the Eye is a base 12 (cost 4 + 2 for roaming = 6) and with a scimitar (cost 1 more for 7) could be a base 14 with the potential to be &quot;pumped&quot; if twilight was left in the pool (in this case 3 of the 10 would be left).  Morgul Hunter is a base 9 which becomes a base 12 spotting 3 companions (cost of 5 + 2 roaming = 7).  Armed with a scimitar he becomes a base 14 (increasing the total cost to 8) with the potential to be pumped to a 16 (with the remaining 2 twilight).<br>
Weathertop was tried since most Nazgul are already fierce and this site would be less devastating that Weather Hills if our opponent was playing wraiths.<br>
In fact, the dream turn occurred once where the opponent put 12 in the pool (4 for Aragorn; 1 for his bow; 1 for athelas; 3 to move; and 3 for the site)and were met with a Morgul Hunter (base 9 + 3 spotting for 12) armed with a scimitar (base 14) with 4 twilight left in the pool (5 for the Hunter; 2 for roaming and 1 for the scimitar; using 8 of the available 12)  Aragorn was overwhelmed when the scimitar pumped to 16 AND then Gandalf died when Enheartened Foe made the Hunter fierce with 2 left in the pool to make the Hunter a 16 once again.<br>
After much playing, however, the conclusion was reached that it wasn&#39;t the lack of twilight which prevented this play as much as it was the occasional Hobbit Stealth or Hobbit Intuition.  Most fellowships were adding plenty of twilight on their first turn so that the extra 2 generated via Weathertop wasn&#39;t worth the tradeoff of being able to prevent stealth events.  Make your own decisions about what you are likely to see.<br>
Site 3.  Rivendell Terrace.  Could be the Bedroom or the Valley.  I chose the Terrace to minimize the opportunity for Hobbit/Elf draw tricks which seem more prevalent than Gondor ones.<br>
Site 4.  Moria Lake.  Was originally Mithril Mine to allow for an early scimitar to be replayed.  That sounded right in theory until a session of play testing versus the Swarm clearly demonstrated the risks associated with this choice.<br>
Site 6.  Only became the Woods after many long play testing sessions.  Too often the need to Versatility to survive the mid game outweighed the disadvantage of allowing my opponent to do the same.  I would much prefer this to be the Glade but cannot bring myself to change it.<br>
Site 7.  Albert argues against the Confluence.  Archery hates the Wilderland.  Silverlode Banks by default.<br>
Site 8.  The Shores for maximum twilight.<br>
Site 9.  Emyn Muil.  These minions are much easier to exert with.  This makes the use of Hate more efficient and makes the use of this site more viable.  Just remember if you are holding an Enheartend Foe at this point use it instead of the site to make a minion fierce.<br>
<br>
CONCLUSION<br>
<br>
This is only one example of adapting to a particular metagame.  That is all I really ever intended it to be.  I had originally wanted to include some comment about specific match ups but this has already gone on much longer than I expected.  If you have questions remaining feel free to d-mail them to me and I will do my best to answer them.<br>
<br>
As a community we are in a very interesting period of time.  We have all found a new game to play which we dearly love.  We all want to become the best player we can be.  We read everything we can find about the game in an effort to learn as much as possible.  We spend endless hours experimenting with ideas and concepts.  We take those ideas to tournaments and put them to the test.  Then for some inexplicable reason we fall into the same mental trap so familiar to those of us with a debating background:  we believe we have all the answers.  The evidence supporting this contention can be found in the myriad of reviews of material submitted to this site.  It is astonishing to count the number of reviews which sound something like:  I like this about what you wrote BUT it is BETTER to use x, y, or z.&quot;<br>
Better for whom?  You?  Me?  Everyone?  What exactly are you suggesting when you write this?  Are you contending that there is a &quot;best&quot; deck for everyone and for all time?  Do you argue that your particular experience is universal and therefore applicable to the rest of us?  I think what we mean to say when we argue &quot;better&quot; is, that in our experience and in our location, we have found alternate choices to be more productive.  Fair enough.<br>
<br>
All metagame choices are assumption based and predictive in nature.  Conclusions are based upon all available information at a given moment in time and are never permanent and obviously never universal.  We need to ask ourselves important questions when reading any given submission:  What assumptions about the metagame is the author making?  Are those assumptions relevant to my particular circumstance?  Would this idea work where I play?  What changes would I need to make in order to be successful with this idea?  How would my &quot;best&quot; deck fare against this approach?<br>
<br>
Two final thoughts:<br>
<br>
Yes, I appreciate the irony that this will now be reviewed.  Double tech points to the first person who writes:  &quot;I&#39;ve seen better.&quot;<br>
<br>
Yes, I purposefully left &quot;Inquest&quot; off of the title AND submitted this as an article.  Though I must admit I did consider resubmitting it as a deck.  Something like:<br>
&quot;Condition Free Zone - Inquest - Revised&quot;   ;)<br>
<br>
Happy Valentine&#39;s Day!<br>
